            <section class="prose mt-10">
              <h2>How this mortgage refinance calculator works</h2>
              <p>
                This calculator compares your existing mortgage with a potential
                refinance. It shows:
              </p>
              <ul>
                <li>New monthly payment vs. your current payment</li>
                <li>Lifetime interest savings (or extra cost)</li>
                <li>Break-even point based on closing costs</li>
                <li>Loan-to-value (LTV) and cash-out capacity</li>
                <li>Net savings over a custom time horizon</li>
              </ul>

              <h3>1. Monthly payment formula</h3>
              <p>
                For both your current and new mortgage, the calculator uses the
                standard amortizing loan formula:
              </p>
              <div class="formula-box">
                <p>Monthly payment \( M \) is:</p>
                <p>\[ M = P \times \frac{r(1+r)^n}{(1+r)^n - 1} \]</p>
                <ul>
                  <li>\( P \) = loan principal (balance)</li>
                  <li>\( r \) = monthly interest rate (APR ÷ 12)</li>
                  <li>\( n \) = total number of monthly payments</li>
                </ul>
              </div>

              <h3>2. Remaining interest vs. new interest</h3>
              <p>The tool estimates:</p>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  <strong>Remaining interest on current loan</strong> = current
                  payment × remaining months − remaining balance
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Total interest on new loan</strong> = new payment ×
                  new term months − new loan amount
                </li>
              </ul>
              <p>Lifetime interest savings are then:</p>
              <div class="formula-box">
                \[ \text{Interest savings} = I_{\text{current remaining}} -
                I_{\text{new total}} \]
              </div>

              <h3>3. Break-even point</h3>
              <p>
                The break-even point tells you how long it takes for your
                monthly savings to recover the refinance closing costs:
              </p>
              <div class="formula-box">
                <p>
                  \[ \text{Break-even (months)} = \frac{\text{Closing
                  costs}}{\text{Monthly savings}} \]
                </p>
                <p>
                  \[ \text{Break-even (years)} = \frac{\text{Break-even
                  (months)}}{12} \]
                </p>
              </div>
              <p>
                If your monthly payment goes up (for example, when shortening
                the term), the calculator shows that break-even is not
                applicable.
              </p>

              <h3>4. Loan-to-value (LTV) and cash-out</h3>
              <p>Your new loan amount is calculated as:</p>
              <div class="formula-box">
                \[ \text{New loan} = \text{Current balance} + \text{Cash-out} +
                \begin{cases} \text{Closing costs}, & \text{if rolled into loan}
                \\ 0, & \text{if paid out-of-pocket} \end{cases} \]
              </div>
              <p>The new LTV ratio is:</p>
              <div class="formula-box">
                \[ \text{LTV} = \frac{\text{New loan}}{\text{Home value}} \times
                100\% \]
              </div>
              <p>
                If the new LTV exceeds the maximum you entered (for example,
                80%), the calculator flags a warning.
              </p>

              <h3>5. Time horizon analysis</h3>
              <p>
                Refinancing only makes sense if you keep the loan long enough.
                The slider lets you choose how many years you expect to keep the
                mortgage. For that horizon, the calculator compares:
              </p>
              <ul>
                <li>Total principal &amp; interest paid on the current loan</li>
                <li>
                  Total principal &amp; interest paid on the new loan (including
                  closing costs if rolled in)
                </li>
                <li>Net savings (or extra cost) over that period</li>
              </ul>

              <h2>When does refinancing a mortgage make sense?</h2>
              <p>Refinancing can be beneficial when:</p>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  You can lower your rate by at least 0.5–1.0 percentage points
                </li>
                <li>
                  You plan to stay in the home longer than the break-even period
                </li>
                <li>
                  You want to shorten your term and can afford a higher payment
                </li>
                <li>
                  You can remove mortgage insurance (PMI) by lowering your LTV
                </li>
                <li>
                  You are consolidating high-interest debt into a lower-rate
                  mortgage and have a plan to avoid re-accumulating debt
                </li>
              </ul>

              <h3>Situations where refinancing may not be worth it</h3>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  You plan to sell or move before reaching the break-even point
                </li>
                <li>
                  Your new rate is only slightly lower and closing costs are
                  high
                </li>
                <li>
                  You extend your term significantly and end up paying more
                  total interest
                </li>
                <li>
                  You use cash-out for short-lived expenses and increase
                  long-term debt
                </li>
              </ul>

              <h2>Practical tips before you refinance</h2>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  <strong>Compare multiple lenders.</strong> Small rate or fee
                  differences can change your break-even point.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Ask for a loan estimate.</strong> This shows detailed
                  closing costs, points, and any prepayment penalties.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Check your credit.</strong> A higher credit score can
                  qualify you for better rates.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Consider your overall plan.</strong> Make sure
                  refinancing fits with retirement, savings, and other financial
                  goals.
                </li>
              </ul>

